{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608547"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:32:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:32:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16002"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16002"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8693"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73463"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8693"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16002"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58933"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"8658"},{"type":"tags","id":"8659"},{"type":"tags","id":"8662"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20803"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73463"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, specific tissue interactions are required for the formation of the central nervous system. One critical structure signals to the overlying ectoderm to initiate neurulation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the signalling relationship in neural tube formation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neural tube induces notochord formation","Notochord induces neural tube formation","Somites induce neural tube formation","Neural tube induces somite formation","Somites induce notochord formation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enotochord \u003C/strong\u003Ecaused\u003Cstrong\u003E neural tube formation\u003C/strong\u003E via a process called neural induction. The notochord, forming during gastrulation, releases molecular signals that cause the ectoderm to thicken and form the neural plate. This plate folds to create the neural tube, which then turns into the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural tube induces notochord formation\u003C/strong\u003E - This reverses the actual sequence; the notochord forms first and induces neural tube formation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESomites induce neural tube formation\u003C/strong\u003E - While somites play important roles in development, they are not the primary inducer of neural tube formation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural tube induces somite formation\u003C/strong\u003E - Somites develop from paraxial mesoderm, not through neural tube induction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESomites induce notochord formation\u003C/strong\u003E - The notochord develops before somite formation during gastrulation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The notochord induces the overlying ectoderm to form the neural tube during neurulation.","Neural tube formation is a key step in central nervous system development."],"references":["Gaillard R, Steegers EA, de Jongste JC, Hofman A, Jaddoe VW. Tracking of fetal growth characteristics during different trimesters and the risks of adverse birth outcomes. Int J Epidemiol. 2014 Aug;43(4):1140-53. doi: 10.1093/ije/dyu036. Epub 2014 Mar 5. PMID: 24603318; PMCID: PMC4258770","Chen X, Liu H, Li Y, Zhang W, Zhou A, Xia W, Xu S. First-trimester fetal size, accelerated growth in utero, and child neurodevelopment in a cohort study. BMC Med. 2024 Apr 29;22(1):181. doi: 10.1186/s12916-024-03390-3. PMID: 38685041; PMCID: PMC11059611","Godfrey KM, Inskip HM, Hanson MA. The long-term effects of prenatal development on growth and metabolism. Semin Reprod Med. 2011 May;29(3):257-65. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1275518. Epub 2011 Jul 18. PMID: 21769765; PMCID: PMC3685133","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58933"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16002"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58933"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T21:19:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T21:20:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8693"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73463"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7